<paragraph id="475A737767D5623E375F8623E8BEAA62" pageNumber="21">
Key to the species of 
<taxonomicName id="34BFF47053EA2F3E8F0EE0130F6E8C56" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0707F8C9-8786-4D4C-8F2F-D9F66C7B96BF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Trachyscorpia Ginsburg 1953:23, 57" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Trachyscorpia</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6D4A34B87F7620E4E51E0EA985A04B63" type="key">
<paragraph id="FE3F3DD46C2D34BFC7A2A279C45E330D" pageNumber="21">
1a. Dorsal-fin spines usually 12; vertebrae 25; swimbladder absent ........................ subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="E18EC01490A31EEF84B32A3ECC60721C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Trachyscorpia">Trachyscorpia</taxonomicName>
2
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1BCF5E9B047BA8A6FA98361F3CFF29F6" pageNumber="21">
1b. Dorsal-fin spines usually 13; vertebrae 26; swimbladder present .......................... subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="99D85723D168F19D060BF93056864B6D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D5DE802B-B69B-40F4-B1AA-BF04007442BA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Mesoscorpia Trachyscorpia Eschmeyer 1969:50" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">Mesoscorpia</taxonomicName>
3
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DAE3DA6EC5FE397E3B817E1864CC8607" pageNumber="21">
2a. Distributed in western Atlantic Ocean ................................... 
<taxonomicName id="B44AAA6FE7601640D89AA3FB4F2BCEAE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="cristulata" subGenus="Trachyscorpia" subSpecies="cristulata">T. (T.) cristulata cristulata (Goode &amp; Bean)</taxonomicName>
A
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BBD8D329DEBB3C7B1A93588A4AC142E1" pageNumber="21">
2b. Distributed in eastern Atlantic Ocean ................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="25AD933DFF943EAA66D6C451EC116D54" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="cristulata" subGenus="Trachyscorpia" subSpecies="echinata">T. (T.) cristulata echinata (Koehler)</taxonomicName>
A
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="22B5C92CC3F0E867F29E5E3414EC30FD" pageNumber="21">
3a. Tympanic spines usually absent (at least one side of head); upper-jaw lip poorly developed, premaxillary teeth exposed laterally; scales on lateral surface of maxilla; no blackish saddles on body in preserved specimens; body depth relatively shallow (32-35% of SL); orbit diameter relatively small (12-14% of SL); head profile concave or straight, and eyes oriented dorsolaterally ....................................................... ................................. 
<taxonomicName id="0CB17A56DB4D1A95D6AB1B237BBBDFA3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF345025-EF7E-432B-B370-B010B63DB47E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Trachyscorpia Mesoscorpia eschmeyeri Whitley 1970:245" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eschmeyeri" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">T. (M.) eschmeyeri Whitley</taxonomicName>
B (southeastern Atlantic and southern Indo -West Pacific)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ECDE489F296D4D86BC0C2EFCC90E40D3" pageNumber="21">3b. Tympanic spines always present; upper-jaw lip well developed, covering premaxillary tooth band laterally; no scales on lateral surface of maxilla; 4 blackish saddles on body in preserved specimens; body depth relatively deep (34-42% of SL); orbit diameter relatively large (14-18% of SL); head profile convex, and eyes oriented almost laterally ........................................................................................................ 4</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A21EBD551F61E0D8EFC13AC888C8E53" pageNumber="21">
4a. Scale rows in longitudinal series 57-63; second pelvic-fin soft ray relatively short (18-25% SL, mean 20%), shorter than upper-jaw length; first anal-fin spine relatively short (5-8% of SL, mean 6%); pelvicfin spine relatively short (9-16% of SL, mean 13%) ................ 
<taxonomicName id="6BD303BFADEC8A88E4D6CB756A30AB04" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carnomagula" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">T. (M.) carnomagula</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="FE1ED7ECC7F2C4DC0218937A90DC193A" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Australasia)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="44E9DA29BC6DBE6AAD807B6DEB407587" pageNumber="21">
4b. Scale rows in longitudinal series 50-53; second pelvic-fin soft ray relatively long (23-29% SL, mean 26%), longer than upper-jaw length; first anal-fin spine relatively long (8-9% of SL, mean 9%); pelvic-fin spine relatively long (15-17% of SL, mean 16%)......................................................................................... ........................................................................ 
<taxonomicName id="0A5E00B31A74D2F13D37977DD4157AFA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="longipedicula" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">T. (M.) longipedicula</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B6014D1F229237698B14C17376ABD5D1" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(southwestern Indian Ocean)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B95F14EE806011CEBCF21E07B4CB49A5" pageNumber="22">
A Eschmeyer (1969) recognized the two allopatric subspecies in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="BF47E0DADBF35EE50E19DB648AF3EFFF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Trachyscorpia">Trachyscorpia</taxonomicName>
. However, diagnostic characters separating the two remain unclear (see Discussion).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6AA6F7D8E01C0AEE06BDDDE12FD9946D" pageNumber="22">
B 
<taxonomicName id="B1E8EACB927EE250CE904FF36C507300" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:CF345025-EF7E-432B-B370-B010B63DB47E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Trachyscorpia Mesoscorpia eschmeyeri Whitley 1970:245" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="eschmeyeri" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">T. (M.) eschmeyeri</taxonomicName>
has previously been recognized as 
<taxonomicName id="23F8B5EE1A733F3287644A4DE878DE49" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sebastidae" genus="Trachyscorpia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="capensis" subGenus="Mesoscorpia">T. (M.) capensis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
